## Part 2: What Each Level Can Do

### Level 1 — Reader (Unregistered)
- Read all content
- View all discussion pages, revision histories, and contribution records
- **Pending changes contribution**: Can submit edits, but they enter a pending-changes queue — visible to the reader themselves, but not shown to other users until approved by a Contributor (Level 2+)

> [!NOTE]
> **Design Decision — Pending Changes for Readers**: Your instinct is right. At early stage with low traffic, allowing pending-changes edits from unregistered users creates a wider contribution funnel without quality risk. As the platform scales and vandalism risk increases, this can be tightened to require registration for any editing. This is a reversible decision.

### Level 2 — Contributor (Registered)
- Everything Level 1 can do
- Edits go **live immediately** — visible in the Recent Changes feed, subject to community review
- Submit new notes/articles
- Participate in all discussion spaces (Report discussions, User discussion pages, Subject Group forums)
- Maintain a public user profile with contribution history
- Follow/watch notes for notifications
- Flag content issues (inline tags: citation needed, outdated, unclear, disputed)

### Level 3 — Recognized Contributor
- Everything Level 2 can do
- **One-click revert** of edits identified as harmful (rollback equivalent), with automatic edit summary
- **Mark flagged issues as resolved** (currently only senior_validator/admin can do this)
- **Fast-track minor corrections** (typo fixes, broken citation fixes) that bypass the standard review scrutiny
- Participate in **peer review** for note quality tier advancement
- Bypass any pending-changes restrictions (their edits are always immediately visible)

### Level 4 — Senior Scholar
- Everything Level 3 can do
- **Close content discussions** and record the consensus reached (with the non-participation rule: cannot close a discussion they contributed to)
- **Advance notes to higher quality tiers** when criteria are met
- Participate in **dispute resolution** as a neutral third party
- **Mentor** subject-area contributor groups (formal mentor role within groups)
- **Propose content structure changes** (merging notes, splitting notes, creating new topic nodes) for community discussion

### Level 5 — Steward
- Everything Level 4 can do
- Apply and remove **page protection** (standard, extended, full, pending-changes)
- **Block users** temporarily or permanently (following graduated response policy)
- **Delete or restore content**
- Resolve **escalated disputes** that community discussion hasn't resolved
- **Grant specific tool access** to lower-level users when warranted
- Manage platform content structure (adding/removing/merging content categories)

*Steward appointment requires public nomination, community review period, community vote. Not permanent — reviewable through same process.*

### Level 6 — Governance Council
- Initiate formal review of Steward conduct
- Execute community consensus decisions to appoint/remove Stewards
- Maintain public record of governance decisions
- Propose platform-wide policy changes for community discussion

*Cannot unilaterally remove a Steward. 3-5 members, elected periodically by community.*

