## Part 4: Level Advancement — How Users Jump Between Levels

### The Combined Threshold Model

Level advancement requires **both** reputation points AND acceptance rate to be above set minimums. This prevents two gaming scenarios:

1. **Volume gaming**: Someone doing hundreds of typo fixes (high acceptance rate, low reputation) — blocked because their reputation is too low
2. **One-shot brilliance**: Someone with one amazing contribution but no sustained track record — blocked because their acceptance count is below threshold

### Should Contribution Volume Be a Third Metric?

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Your question answered**: Yes, I recommend contribution volume as a third metric, but framed differently. Instead of "number of edits," use **"number of accepted contributions"** — which is essentially the denominator of the acceptance rate. This solves the one-brilliant-contribution problem without rewarding raw activity. A user needs N accepted contributions minimum, plus a reputation score above M, plus an acceptance rate above P%.

### Proposed Thresholds

| Level | To Advance From → To | Accepted Contributions | Acceptance Rate | Reputation Score |
|-------|---------------------|----------------------|----------------|-----------------|
| 2 → 3 | Contributor → Recognized Contributor | ≥15 accepted edits | ≥70% | ≥50 points |
| 3 → 4 | Recognized Contributor → Senior Scholar | ≥75 accepted edits | ≥80% | ≥400 points |
| 4 → 5 | Senior Scholar → Steward | Community nomination + vote process | N/A | N/A |
| 5 → 6 | Steward → Governance Council | Community election | N/A | N/A |

> [!NOTE]
> **Calibration Principle**: Level 3 should be reachable by any genuinely engaged student within **a few weeks** of active participation. If 15 accepted edits and 50 reputation points takes longer than 3-4 weeks for an engaged contributor, the thresholds are too high. Level 4 should take several months of sustained quality work.

> [!WARNING]  
> **These thresholds are placeholders.** They MUST be calibrated once real contribution patterns are observable. The principle matters more than the numbers.

### Additional Requirement for Level 4

Level 4 (Senior Scholar) adds a qualitative requirement beyond the numbers: **demonstrated constructive participation in discussions and dispute resolution.** This cannot be purely algorithmic — it requires the community to observe that this contributor engages constructively, not just quantitatively. This could be operationalized as:

- A minimum number of discussion contributions in closed threads (showing they participate in governance)
- Peer endorsements from multiple existing Level 4+ users
- No active misconduct warnings on their record

